data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The `EnableSyncOverAsync()` configuration option (which you used in .NET 10) no longer exists.

All four of your synchronous calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime:

| Method | Issue |
|--------|-------|
| `ToList()` | ❌ Sync not supported |
| `First(...)` | ❌ Sync not supported |
| `Count()` | ❌ Sync not supported |
| `SaveChanges()` | ❌ Sync not supported |

## The Fix: Go Fully Async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through your call chain (controllers, services, etc.). The Cosmos SDK v4 is inherently async-only — EF Core 11 simply stops pretending otherwise.
